# SOLID Principles

Apply SOLID principles rigorously in all code:

## Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
- Each class should have only one reason to change
- A class should have only one job or responsibility
- If a class does multiple things, split it into multiple classes
- Example: Separate data access logic from business logic

## Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
- Software entities should be open for extension but closed for modification
- Use interfaces and abstract classes to allow extension without modifying existing code
- Prefer composition and polymorphism over direct modification
- Example: Use strategy pattern instead of if/else chains

## Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
- Derived classes must be substitutable for their base classes
- Subtypes must be able to replace their base types without breaking the application
- Don't override methods in ways that violate the base class contract
- Example: If a method expects a base class, any subclass should work correctly

## Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
- Clients should not be forced to depend on interfaces they don't use
- Create specific interfaces instead of one general-purpose interface
- Split large interfaces into smaller, more focused ones
- Example: Separate read and write interfaces instead of one CRUD interface

## Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
- High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules; both should depend on abstractions
- Depend on abstractions (interfaces) rather than concrete implementations
- Use dependency injection to provide dependencies
- Example: Inject repository interfaces instead of concrete database classes
